          • [ - ] Nico1 - member since 22-Jun-16

            @pyt55 @pyt55 De Gea is done as a top level goalkeeper. The best goal keepers these days can play out from the back, they command their boxes and they rush out the box to stop onrushing attackers. De Gea is levels behind the likes of Alisson and Ederson at playing out from the back as his pass success % shows. He simply doesn't have the physicality to dominate his penalty area. And in terms of rushing out of the box he only has 2 sweeper clearances all season which is by far less than nearly every other PL keeper (Alisson has 7 and he's played 9 games less than De Gea). De Gea built his reputation on shot stopping but even that is not what it once was, only Leno has made more errors leading to goals than De Gea since the beginning of last season. De Gea has also made big errors in champions league matches against Barcelona and Sevilla as well as errors for Spain which have cost him his place in the national team.

            49 weeks ago

          • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

            @Nico1- It's unfair to compare De Gea and Leno playing behind poor defences versus Alisson playing behind a solid one given the fact a poor defence impacts a GK. The criteria for what determines an "error" is also highly subjective. However, the best stat to highlight de Gea's decline is in "Adjusted Save %". He is in a negative figure meaning that he makes fewer saves, by way of %, than he should. As you say, his reputation was built on his ability as a shot stopper.
